From james.knott at rogers.com  Mon Jan 11 07:11:29 2016
From: james.knott at rogers.com (James Knott)
Date: Mon, 11 Jan 2016 07:11:29 -0500
Subject: [GTALUG] (question) What is the purpose of UID==GID?
In-Reply-To: <20160111083012.GA9905@node1.localdomain>
References: <20160111083012.GA9905@node1.localdomain>
Message-ID: <56939BF1.9090205@rogers.com>

On 01/11/2016 03:30 AM, William Park wrote:
> Just curious...
>
> I noticed that distros tend to create user account with unique UID and
> unique GID (and usually both are the same id).  For example, UID=1000
> and GID=1000.
>
> What is the reason behind it?

As I understand it, it's so you can give some, but not all, other users
group access to your stuff.  With a common GID, it's everyone or no one.


From alvin at netvel.net  Mon Jan 11 07:42:12 2016
From: alvin at netvel.net (Alvin Starr)
Date: Mon, 11 Jan 2016 07:42:12 -0500
Subject: [GTALUG] (question) What is the purpose of UID==GID?
In-Reply-To: <20160111083012.GA9905@node1.localdomain>
References: <20160111083012.GA9905@node1.localdomain>
Message-ID: <5693A324.4070208@netvel.net>

GID does not have to equal UID.
It just does by convention.
If you can keep the relationship then it makes admin a slight bit easier.

For example if you do an ls  and get

   4 drwxrwxr-x.  2  108 108    4096 Feb 23  2015 foo.bar

you know the owner/group are set to a reasonable value as opposed to

   4 drwxr-xr-x.  7 1000 500    4096 Dec 14  2012  bar.baz

where you now need to lookup the GID for UID 1000.


On 01/11/2016 03:30 AM, William Park wrote:
> Just curious...
